  "created": "2025-10-14",
  "description": "E. coli's phosphate (Pi) regulation is crucial for survival across varying environmental Pi concentrations. Under low Pi conditions, the Pho regulon, orchestrated by the PhoR/PhoB two-component system, activates a suite of genes. These include high-affinity Pi transporters like the Pst system, enzymes for Pi scavenging such as alkaline phosphatase (PhoA), and pathways for membrane lipid remodeling to conserve phosphorus. The Pst system itself acts as a sensor, inhibiting PhoR's activity when Pi is abundant. Conversely, normal to high intracellular Pi levels trigger distinct regulatory cascades. High Pi influences the phosphorylation state of the phosphotransferase system (PTS) components, particularly leading to the accumulation of unphosphorylated EIIA^Glc (EIIA^Glc-P-free). This, in turn, activates adenylate cyclase (CyaA), increasing cellular cAMP levels. The cAMP-Crp complex then acts as a global regulator, influencing carbon metabolism and, under specific stress conditions, activating a stress-mediated cell death pathway. Additionally, E. coli manages Pi through polyphosphate (PolyP) metabolism, serving as a dynamic intracellular Pi reserve, and tightly regulates the synthesis of essential Pi-containing cofactors like pyridoxal 5'-phosphate (PLP) via feedback inhibition, ensuring precise Pi homeostasis and cellular fitness.",
  "id": "ecoli_phosphate_regulation",
  "keywords": [
    "phosphate",
    "regulation"
  ],
